ANTHRAX PARCEL - PAKISTAN (02): (ISLAMABAD)
*******************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Wed 1 Feb 2012
Source: Hindustan Times, Press Trust of India report [edited]
http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/Pakistan/Woman-professor-mailed-anthrax-parcel-to-Pak-PM-s-office/Article1-805340.aspx


In the 1st incident of its kind, a woman university professor from southern Sindh province sent a parcel containing deadly anthrax powder to the Pakistani prime minister's secretariat, police said on Wednesday [1 Feb 2012]. The incident triggered an alarm prompting police and security agencies to launch an investigation.

No one was affected by the anthrax and investigators were yet to determine the motive of the professor from Jamshoro University, officials were quoted as saying by the Pakistani media. It could not immediately be ascertained whether the professor had been arrested.

The parcel was received at the prime minister's secretariat in October last year [2011]. Earlier, police officials in Islamabad had said the parcel was sent to the premier's secretariat about 20 days ago.

Police launched an investigation and registered a case against "unknown persons" after a laboratory confirmed the parcel contained anthrax, they said. The parcel was tested at a laboratory of the Council for Scientific and Industrial Research [CSIR]. A police team has been sent to Jamshoro to investigate.

Though the Taliban and other militant groups have carried out scores of bombings and suicide attacks in recent years, there have been no reported instances of them using letters or parcels with poisonous materials like anthrax.

